## Connecting Risk to Controls — The Core GRC Translation

Day 89 produced the current-state risk register — seven risks with evolved ratings, residual risk assessments, and two integrated patterns: the threat environment elevation for credential theft and ransomware (RS-001, RS-004), and the AU-12 detection gap affecting multiple risk residuals (RS-001, RS-005). The risk register tells the story of what the program is protecting against. Day 90 answers the question the risk register raises: what is the program actually doing about it?

I want to be direct about what the control implementation plan adds at the capstone stage that earlier sections did not already cover. Days 47 through 60 produced the full SSP control implementation descriptions — every selected control with its implementation narrative. Days 62 through 64 produced the formal security assessment results. The capstone control section is not a repetition of that work. Its purpose is to show the relationship between the risk register and the control set — which controls address which risks, whether the control coverage is adequate given current risk ratings, and where the gap between documented control implementation and demonstrated control effectiveness currently exists.

This is the risk-to-control traceability that completes the compliance mapping from Day 88. Day 88 traced from regulatory requirement to control to evidence. Day 90 traces from risk to control to current effectiveness status.

