### RS-002: Application Layer Vulnerability (MODERATE)

**Primary controls addressing this risk:**

*SC-5 (Denial of Service Protection) / SC-7 (Boundary Protection):* AWS WAF with OWASP Core Rule Set and custom OpenMRS-specific rules. Implementation status: COMPLIANT per SAR; WAF rule log review included in monthly monitoring. Effectiveness evidence: WAF blocks SQL injection, XSS, and path traversal attempts before reaching application layer. Current state: effective.

*SI-2 (Flaw Remediation):* Monthly OWASP Dependency-Check scans; AWS Inspector monthly EC2 OS vulnerability scans; patch SLA compliance tracked at KPI-VM-1 (97% in Q1). Implementation status: COMPLIANT. Effectiveness evidence: no High or Critical unpatched vulnerabilities identified in Q1 monitoring. Current state: effective.

*CM-3 (Configuration Change Control):* Module governance requiring ISSO notification and SIA for all OpenMRS module additions. Implementation status: documented; M-002 finding demonstrated IAM policy change outside CM-3 (IT Administrator pattern). Effectiveness evidence: no unauthorized module installations detected in Q1; two CM-3 compliance lapses involved infrastructure changes, not application changes. Current state: effective for application layer; process compliance gap in infrastructure layer.

*CM-7 (Least Functionality):* Unnecessary services, ports, and protocols disabled on EC2. Implementation status: COMPLIANT per SAR hardening checklist. Current state: effective.

**Control coverage assessment for RS-002:** WAF and vulnerability scanning provide strong defense-in-depth for known vulnerability exploitation. CM-3 module governance prevents supply chain compromise through unauthorized module introduction. Principal residual risk (zero-day before patch availability) is not addressable through additional controls — it is managed through WAF behavioral analysis and rapid patch deployment discipline.

