## The Highest-Priority Control Gap

Looking across the full control set, the single highest-priority gap — the one that both the risk register and the control effectiveness summary point to — is the human layer.

The technical controls are working. Encryption is compliant and continuously monitored. MFA is enforced and bypass-resistant. WAF is blocking application-layer attacks. Backup architecture passed its quarterly restoration test. Configuration monitoring is catching drift within hours of occurrence.

What the technical controls cannot do is prevent a staff member from clicking a targeted phishing email that captures both their password and their TOTP code in real time. And what the audit logging currently cannot do is detect the credential probing that precedes a targeted attack — because denied access events are not being logged.

Both gaps are addressable. The phishing simulation program addresses the human layer effectiveness measurement gap. The AU-12 remediation addresses the denied-access detection gap. Together, they close the two most significant control effectiveness gaps in the entire program.

Neither is technically complex. Both are organizationally straightforward. The reason they are second-year priorities rather than completed work is resource prioritization — the first authorization year's energy went into building and assessing the technical control foundation. The second year's opportunity is demonstrating that the human layer is as disciplined as the technical layer.

