## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The gap between documented control implementation and demonstrated control effectiveness is illustrated precisely by the **2020 University of Vermont Health Network ransomware attack**, in which the organization's security team had implemented many of the right technical controls — endpoint detection, network segmentation, backup systems — but the ransomware attack still succeeded in taking the EHR system offline for several weeks because the human layer (phishing email that delivered the initial malware) had not been addressed with the same rigor as the technical layer.

The recovery took weeks rather than days in part because the backup restoration procedures, while documented, had not been fully tested under the specific conditions of the incident — a lesson that maps directly to the OpenMRS IR-3 tabletop gap (documented ransomware playbook, unexecuted tabletop scenario).

For the OpenMRS program, the UVM case is both a validation that the technical architecture is on the right track (network segmentation, backup systems) and a caution that technical controls alone are insufficient — the human layer and the demonstrated readiness through exercises are what convert documented capability into actual resilience.

